{"type":"message","id":"1b6e862f","parentId":"3c430f87","timestamp":"2026-05-08T23:01:39.291Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The crash still happens! And it's still the same `\\x1b[2m` ANSI escape sequence issue. This means it's NOT from the MCP servers I just disabled (brave, opencode-enforce, comfyui-mcp). It must be from one of the ACTIVE MCP servers.\n\nLet me look at the new mcp-stderr.log after the restart to see what each server outputs. The crash is happening almost immediately after gateway starts (06:00:37).\n\nThe error message shows: `input_value='\\x1b[2m2026-05-08T23:00:...` - this looks like a timestamp `2026-05-08T23:00:` which suggests it's from a log or debug output, not from the MCP server's actual startup.\n\n\nI need to check what's happening with the current active MCP servers. There are several running: socraticode, puppeteer, filesystem, sequential-thinking, memory, exa, context7, debugger, mcp-server-terminal, server-everything, zapier. The server-everything output I saw contained \"[smithery] Starting MCP server\" which is formatted text, not JSON. Looking at the error message `\\x1b[2m2026-05-08T23:00:...input stream terminated`, this could be from socraticode or one of the other active servers that's outputting log text instead of proper JSON responses.\n\nLet me check the mcp-stderr.log to see if socraticode is the culprit, or possibly one of the Python-based servers like context7, exa, mcp-server-terminal, or mcp-server-everything since they're running on Node.js and might be emitting ANSI-colored output.\n\nI should focus on which server is actually emitting the `\\x1b` ANSI sequences that are corrupting the stream, since that's what's causing the JSON parsing to fail. The `input stream terminated` error suggests something is writing to stdout and then the connection closes unexpectedly.\n\nLooking at the logs, the old PID 2521801 crashed at 06:00:37 but the new instance 2525755 started at 06:00:53, so the crash is happening very early in the startup sequence. The MCP stderr log only has entries from 06:00:46 onward, which is after the crash, so I need to capture the logs from the very beginning of the new gateway process to catch which server is causing the issue.\n","thinkingSignature":"5f094c316b3a3198d77c74d67beefd35c55b0c6a0233c55d3e84a69446a77ce1"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_kbhoxetfg7ni_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"tail -100 ~/.hermes/logs/mcp-stderr.log | grep -E \"\\x1b|2026-05-08T23:|smithery|socraticode\" | head -20","timeout":10}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_kbhoxetfg7ni_2","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"wc -l ~/.hermes/logs/mcp-stderr.log && tail -50 ~/.hermes/logs/mcp-stderr.log","timeout":10}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":743,"output":634,"cacheRead":94976,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":96353,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778281278623,"responseId":"064d9e4013f87ddfc62dd077f7990d9f"}}
