{"type":"message","id":"c304c4d8","parentId":"dbabb18a","timestamp":"2026-05-08T23:02:28.643Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The crash is happening during graceful shutdown of the previous instance. The previous gateway (2521801) is shutting down and one of the MCP servers (socraticode via smithery) is outputting ANSI color codes before terminating, which corrupts the JSON stream.\n\nThis is a race condition during shutdown. The fix is to improve the cleanup script to be more aggressive with the kill, OR to configure the MCP server stdio reader to be more tolerant of non-JSON output.\n\nBut more importantly - looking at the last line `input stream terminated` - the issue is that the MCP server is being killed while it's in the middle of outputting something, and the partial output includes ANSI codes.\n \nI could disable smithery's output mode if it has one, or filter the ANSI codes before they hit the JSON parser, or just clean up those MCP processes more aggressively in the override. But really, this isn't blocking anything—the gateway restarts successfully and everything works. The 2-minute shutdown is just the graceful timeout waiting for processes that won't terminate cleanly.\n\nThe real issue is that when systemctl calls ExecStopPost, the gateway main process has already exited but the child processes like socraticode running through smithery are still going. The cleanup script handles most of it, but something's still hanging during that shutdown window.\n\nThe timing is suspicious—at 06:00:31 the restart command runs, by 06:00:37 the crash occurs, and 06:00:39 the exit happens. The crash error itself (`input stream terminated`) suggests an MCP server's input stream got cut off while it was mid-output, which could explain why cleanup isn't catching everything. Let me trace through the actual MCP stderr to see which server was still running when things went down.\n\nI'm wondering if the config changes I made (commenting out the problematic servers) weren't picked up by the previous gateway instance before it restarted. The new instance should have loaded the updated config without brave, opencode-enforce-context-mode, and comfyui-mcp. But if the crash happens during shutdown of the old instance, that suggests the issue isn't about loading new config—it's about the old instance's state during termination.\n\nLet me verify whether the current Hermes is actually running with the clean config by checking which MCP servers are actually loaded.\n","thinkingSignature":"3aa0ddbea33a4270a2b68b58a5799e1016694438271b89218f4af99e8c8c6b5f"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_txdcdrggjilo_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ps aux | grep -E \"socraticode|2525755\" | grep -v grep","timeout":5}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_txdcdrggjilo_2","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"journalctl --user -u hermes-gateway --since \"06:00:42\" -n 30 --no-pager 2>&1","timeout":10}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":413,"output":576,"cacheRead":98816,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":99805,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778281327285,"responseId":"064d9e717916e21c7057f9074c9f12d5"}}
