{"type":"message","id":"6a9d7a95","parentId":"239f135b","timestamp":"2026-05-08T23:23:13.866Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the full picture. Let me look at what happened between 06:01 and 06:19 when it timed out.\n\nThe gateway actually started successfully at 06:00:53 and was running fine. It processed messages normally. But at 06:19:47 it was killed due to timeout.\n\nLooking at the gateway.log more carefully... the gateway was running from 06:00:53 to 06:19:47 = 18+ minutes. Then it got killed by systemd with timeout.\n\nThis suggests the gateway didn't respond to a systemd stop request (SIGTERM) within the TimeoutStopSec=45 configured in the override.conf. After 45 seconds of trying to stop gracefully, systemd gave up and sent SIGKILL.\n \nBut the journal shows it took nearly 19 minutes to reach that point, not 45 seconds. The process log indicates it was killed with code=killed, status=9/KILL, which is the final SIGKILL after multiple attempts to shut down gracefully failed.\n\nThe real question is why the gateway took so long to respond to the stop signal in the first place. Looking back at the previous session, the gateway did exit cleanly at 06:00:37 with exit code 1, which triggered an automatic restart. So the startup issue we saw earlier might not be the root cause here—the current timeout could stem from something else entirely.\n","thinkingSignature":"d214720a88a4f1a430acd9a34a991fbed12843a7edcb5807d829f0f908d20080"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_brfotvj1z7w0_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"tail -100 ~/.hermes/logs/gateway.log | grep -v \"^{\" | tail -60","timeout":10}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":1578,"output":340,"cacheRead":103360,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":105278,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778282586694,"responseId":"064da35cc971434ff5c1a52