{"type":"message","id":"96a448e1","parentId":"42114dc2","timestamp":"2026-05-08T23:23:21.837Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have the full picture. Let me analyze:\n\n1. Gateway ran fine from 06:00:53 to 06:17:51 - about 17 minutes of normal operation\n2. At 06:17:51, gateway initiated stop for restart (triggered by `/minimax-workflow` command presumably)\n3. From 06:17:51 to 06:19:00 - graceful shutdown was in progress\n4. At 06:19:00, SIGTERM was received - proper shutdown started\n5. The \"other hermes processes running\" shown at 06:19:00 are all the MCP server child processes (node processes spawned by Hermes gateway)\n\n\n6. The cleanup script tries to terminate these MCP processes but encounters issues where they're not responding to the standard termination signal, forcing systemd to resort to SIGKILL. After the old gateway is killed, a fresh instance starts up and successfully restores connections to Telegram and the API server within seconds, with no actual errors appearing in the gateway log itself—the system is functioning normally.\n\nThe real problem is that systemd's timeout threshold (default 90 seconds) gets exceeded during the shutdown sequence because the MCP server processes are slow to shut down gracefully, triggering the timeout failure. At 06:19:47, the service is marked as failed with a timeout result, but critically, the Restart directive isn't being honored by systemd for this particular failure condition.\n\nNow I'm checking what the override.conf actually specifies for the Restart configuration.\n","thinkingSignature":"dfb13626a1145e54603ca919cdbfa25390cdfd1c1d3feb9b4393682e6e579919"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_5f337g7i0fpo_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"systemctl --user show hermes-gateway.service -p RestartSec,RestartSteps,RestartMaxDelaySec,NRestarts,ActiveState,SubState 2>/dev/null","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7